03991nam a22004935i 9780226869087DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082007ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802268690877 a10.7208/97802268690872doi  a(DE-B1597)524311  a(OCoLC)1058112685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aWalsh, Katherine Cramer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTalking about Race :bCommunity Dialogues and the Politics of Difference /cKatherine Cramer Walsh. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (317 p.) :b21 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Communication, Media, and Public Opinion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Race, Dialogue, and the Practice of Community Life -- t2. Unity and Difference in Civic Life -- t3. Public Talk That Aims to Listen to Difference -- t4. The Community Choice to Pursue Interracial Dialogue -- t5. Choosing the Action of Talk -- t6. Negotiating Unity and Difference -- t7. Scrutinizing and Listening to Stories -- t8. Authority and Legitimacy in Dialogue -- t9. Public Officials and Residents in Dialogue -- t10. Beyond Romance and Demons -- tMethods Appendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is a perennial question: how should Americans deal with racial and ethnic diversity? More than 400 communities across the country have attempted to answer it by organizing discussions among diverse volunteers in an attempt to improve race relations. In Talking about Race, Katherine Cramer Walsh takes an eye-opening look at this strategy to reveal the reasons behind the method and the effects it has in the cities and towns that undertake it. With extensive observations of community dialogues, interviews with the discussants, and sophisticated analysis of national data, Walsh shows that while meeting organizers usually aim to establish common ground, participants tend to leave their discussions with a heightened awareness of differences in perspective and experience. Drawing readers into these intense conversations between ordinary Americans working to deal with diversity and figure out the meaning of citizenship in our society, she challenges many preconceptions about intergroup relations and organized public talk. Finally disputing the conventional wisdom that unity is the only way forward, Walsh prescribes a practical politics of difference that compels us to reassess the place of face-to-face discussion in civic life and the critical role of conflict in deliberative democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226869087423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226869087.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles